Import marks are discreet and on the bottom of the barrel, hidden by the cleaning rod. No ugly importer's information on the receiver!

All numbers match on the rifle with the exception of the floorplate, which is a forced match [most likely replaced during arsenal refurbishment]. There are no signs of rust or pitting anywhere on the rifle. The scope and mount are authentic parts that were refurbished along with the rifle. The PU scope is properly zeroed using the mount for course adjustment, and the reticle is in the center of the field of view. Glass is clear edge-to-edge with no chips of cracks in the lenses. The scope and mount both match the original markings on the receiver, and none are forced matches.

 Included but not pictured are a complete soviet issue cleaning kit, a proper WWII sling [not a reproduction], and 150rds of Brown Bear 174g FMJ-BT ammunition. The scope is zeroed for this bullet because its trajectory most closely resembles the trajectory of the original WWII era 147g flat base ball ammo.

 Asking price is $800, or best reasonable offer. No trades please.

Many more pictures are available. Please Email me if interested!

title: For Sale/Trade:  Yugo Mauser 24/47 all matching with Royal Yugo and German markings
postcontent:
Up for sale is a Yugoslavian Mauser Model 24/47.  This rifle is all matching numbers to include the receiver, barrel, stock, bolt and magazine (magazine is a forced match, the others are not).  

This is not a Mitchell Mauser.  It is import stamped.

Previous arsenal and manufacture markings were scrubbed on this one, but are still visible.
Faintly below the 24/47 markings Royal Yugo markings can be seen, as well as the location of original manufacture (Artillery Technical Institute).  This makes original manufacture prewar (1928-31).  Hard to get a picture of this as it is so faint, but it is there and I certainly welcome anyone to inspect it in person if they wish.

There are also two scrubbed German acceptance stamps, one on the receiver, indicating that the action (not the rifle as it sits today) was seized and put into German service, and one on the bolt release.  So the action certainly saw combat during WWII.

The rifling is nearly flawless.  The rifle does have some surface rust on the receiver, but this is limited and there is no corrosion.  Not pretty but this rifle has been through a lot looking at the number/type of arsenal marks and stock markings.

Cycles great, shoots/groups dead on (though I don't have anywhere to shoot long range, so a little high at 100 yards as expected).

I have taken pictures of the rifle in and out, including all the markings should anyone wish to see more, ask questions etc.  

All and all would make an all matching good shooter with a little bit of history behind it.

(Source for manufacture date/location)

title: For Sale:  Kel-Tec KSG TAN Tactical Shotgun
postcontent:
Kel-Tec KSG TAN Tactical Shotgun 12ga 18.5"

The KSG is Kel-Tec's first entry into the shotgun market. The size, shape and design are similar to the currently available Kel-Tec RFB rifle, but the KSG ejects downward, instead of forward. The simple and reliable pump action feeds from either the left or right tube. The feed side is manually selected by a lever located behind the trigger guard. The lever can be positioned in the center detent in order to easily clear the chamber without feeding another round from either magazine. title: For Sale:  1966 Smith & Wesson Model 36 - Chiefs special
postcontent:
.38 Special
1.875" barrel
Original diamond grips

This was an inheritance and I don't know exactly what it's worth... it is incredibly clean for a 50 year old American legend, and grandpa claimed it was worth a lot.

I've been watching gunbroker, armslist, facebook for weeks and I have yet to see one of these as old as this one listed anywhere, let alone one in this condition, so I guess only collectors know how much it's worth.
See serial number 504xxx in picture. I included serial number ranges at bottom too. (First tip is any 6 digit all numeric is pre-1970)

In other words, this is not a cheap one. It has been preserved 50 years.
NO lowball offers. (Lets just say $600 minimum).

Please email serious offers to REDACTED

*** P2C or P2P required
*** I will ask for your name and dob over the phone to check eligibility before meeting. You must bring your valid permit to carry or permit to purchase, and MN ID.

-----

Condition:
I was told not to clean it (have a pro do it). The barrel and cylinders are dusty but I did use a small toothbrush on small areas to confirm that the barrel rifling and cylinders look like new. 

The little bit of darkening on the grips is from me being an idiot and handling it... they were brighter so apparently I dirtied them by handling it too much in a couple weeks - it just feels so good to hold on to. Again would like to clean but feel I should leave this to a pro - the checkering is sharp and I don't want to wear it down.

The only noticeable flaw is a small scratched area about 1/2" long on the right side of the frame above the cylinder (see pic).

Action perfect.
Cylinder release perfect.
Cylinder lock is tight... I thought maybe too tight but buddy says that is like new.

-----
Serial:
I do not have the official S&W book but I found some internet forums where folks have posted the serial number ranges from the book:
http://www.migunowners.org/forum/archive/index.php/t-92503.html
https://thefiringline.com/forums/showthread.php?t=277680&page=6

For models 36, 37, 38, 49, 50 and pre model number versions.
1950 = start at 1
1952 = 7369 - 21342
1953 = 28916
1955 = 55050 - 75000
1957 = 117770 - 125000
1962 = starts at 295000
1969 = ends at 786544

J serial Prefix serial numbers.
For models 36, 37, 38, 49, 50.

1969-1970 = J1 - J99999
1971-1972 = 1J1 - 999J99
1973-1974 = J100000 - J250000
1975-1976 = J250001 - J370000
1976-1977 = J370001 - J610000
1977-1978 = J610001 - J670000
1979-1980 = J670001 - J760000
1981 = J760001 - J915400
1982 = J915401 - 1J18600
1983 = 1J18601 - 1JXXXX

1955 - 4 screw side plate ends
1957 - stamping of model number at 125000
1966 - flat latch ends
1968 - diamond grips end
1975 - heavy barrel standard
1982 - end pinned barrel 

----------------------------------

Serial range indicates it was manufactured 1962 - 1969.
This does not have the "flat latch" cylinder release so it is 1966 or later.
And the original diamond grips mean it was before those ended 1968.
So it was manufactured 1966-1967, and by the serial we think '66.
